{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505626","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505626"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:33:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:33:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2459"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2459","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2459"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.66,0.29,0.03,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2459"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53388"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2459","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2459"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2459"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38843"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"1"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"5602"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2024"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2027"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15769"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53388","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53388"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 75-year-old man is being assessed in the pre-admission clinic for an elective umbilical hernia repair. He gets central abdominal pain especially at the end of a day, but has no signs of bowel obstruction or overlying skin changes. His medical history includes of type 2 diabetes mellitus which is controlled with diet and his last HbA1c was 6.2%. He also suffers from asthma which he takes a daily preventer and occasional salbutamol 1x per month. He has not needed steroids or hospital admission for many years.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination in the clinic, his blood pressure is 136/92 mmHg, pulse 88/min and temperature 37.2\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. His weight is 120kg and he is 194 cm tall. There are no other abnormalities on examination.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"What is the American Society of Anesthesiologists (ASA) physical score for this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["1","2","3","4","5"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIt is important to have a general idea of the functional status of a comorbid patient and thus the risk posed to them undergoing surgery. This allows a risk benefit discussion to be had regarding the surgery, especially when it is an elective procedure and may not be absolutely necessary. One way to help conceptualise the risk is based on a patient\u2019s ASA score. Although it was originally developed in the USA, the ASA score is now used worldwide as a standardised perioperative evaluation tool. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGenerally, the ASA scoring is as follows:\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EASA 1: \u003C/strong\u003Ehealthy patient, non-smoking and minimal alcohol\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EASA 2: \u003C/strong\u003Emild disease without functional limitation (smoker, social drinker, pregnant, BMI 30-40, well controlled DM/hypertension, mild lung disease)\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EASA 3: \u003C/strong\u003Esystemic disease with some functional limitation (e.g. poorly controlled DM or hypertension, COPD, morbid obesity (\u0026gt;40), heart failure, end stage kidney disease on dialysis, MI \u0026gt;3 months ago)\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EASA 4:\u003C/strong\u003E severe systemic disease that is a threat to life (e.g. MI \u0026lt;3months ago, CVA, severe valve disease, sepsis, ARDS, end stage kidney disease without dialysis)\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EASA 5: \u003C/strong\u003Epatient will not survive without surgery (ruptured aortic aneurysm, massive trauma, intracranial bleed, ischaemic bowel)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EASA 6:\u003C/strong\u003E brain dead patient for organ donation\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBased on the above, this patient has well controlled disease that is not limiting his functional capacity and would be an \u003Cstrong\u003EASA 2.\u00a0\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The ASA scoring allows a patient\u0027s overall anaesthetic risk to be categorised."],"references":["Mayhew D, Mendonca V, Murthy BVS. A review of ASA physical status - historical perspectives and modern developments. Anaesthesia 2019; 74 (3): 373-379."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38843"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2459"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38843","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/38843"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-20T09:42:39+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-20T09:48:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2459"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53388"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"1","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude34","name":"Anaesthesia","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"typ